node.text:
The ”post-workout glow” isn’t a myth ✨🏋🏽‍♂️ 
Yesterday's session 👇🏽 
•Single leg RDL in smith 
40 kg 12 reps x 3 sets each leg 
•Reversed barbell lunges 60 kg 10 reps x 3 sets each leg 
•Hip thrust 160 kg 3 sets until failure 
•Seated leg extension 
85 kg until failure 
90 kg until failure 
95 kg until failure 
100 kg until failure 

I am currently not super motivated(always lose my cravings for the gym when it's hot outside), so when I go I focus on exercises that I enjoy doing. The "real" work will prob start in September, when it's getting less warm outside. At the moment I am just trying to maintain my current physique, I don't really feel like pressuring myself too much right now. Honestly prioritizing my tan and the beach while our short summer lasts🇸🇪🤣🏖

node.text:
Two of my favourite bikini pics from marbella earlier this year💗
I just wanted to show you guys how different my skin looks depending on the light. At first glance, some of you might think that this is an "unedited vs edited" comparison, but none of these pics has been edited in a way to make my skin look smoother. Both are taken outside in natural light with our mirrorless camera. The difference is that the picture to the left was taken in the middle of the day in cloudy/rainy weather, and the picture to the right was taken in the light of a soft sunset. I wouldn't say that I look 100% like either of those pics in real life, I think I am something in between. Either way, I really like both of them and I am not trying to say that one is better than the other, I simply wanted to show this because I personally NEVER knew how much light mattered in pictures until maybe 6 months ago. I could cry sometimes because I hated the way my face looked in pictures, and I almost felt a bit anxious every time we were shooting😅 I didn't know that certain lights can make you look grayish and almost a bit "ill", so I was very confused because I looked normal in the mirror, but in pictures my face looked so tired and colorless. It's the same with the body, some lights will highlight and sharpen every little mark, and some lights will give you a softer and smoother look. 
To some people, this whole thing with the light might be obvious, but to me it wasn't. I've been doing Instagram for 4 years now, and it took me until recently to realize how much impact the light has over the result. I don't want to sound super shallow, like looking "good" in a picture is everything that matters, but I know how much social media affects many of us and I felt that I wanted to share my own thoughts. If I knew earlier how different the skin(and even the features) can look depending on the surrounding light, it would've saved me a lot of confusion about my face especially😂🥲💗

(Note: I don’t have extensions, my hair is naturally long and thick, both on the head and on the rest of my body😬😂)
